00:23:31.342 --> 00:23:34.170
[APPLAUSE]

00:23:34.170 --> 00:23:38.230
Robert Taylor, Richard
Oberbacker, the co-writers--

00:23:38.230 --> 00:23:40.080
where did the two
of you guys come up

00:23:40.080 --> 00:23:41.310
with the idea for this show?

00:23:41.310 --> 00:23:42.726
How long has it
been in the works?

00:23:44.974 --> 00:23:46.640
ROBERT TAYLOR: It's
about four years ago

00:23:46.640 --> 00:23:50.720
we first put pen to paper.

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:56.340
And we had this idea that we
wanted to really pay tribute

00:23:56.340 --> 00:24:03.210
to musicals from The Golden Age,
but come at them from a very

00:24:03.210 --> 00:24:08.340
contemporary perspective, in
that all of the situations

00:24:08.340 --> 00:24:13.630
that MGM musicals tend to gloss
over in a Hollywood fashion,

00:24:13.630 --> 00:24:17.710
we would actually be honest,
the actual circumstances

00:24:17.710 --> 00:24:18.730
of the characters.

00:24:18.730 --> 00:24:20.230
RICHARD OBERACKER:
That was really--

00:24:20.230 --> 00:24:21.730
it was almost like
a thesis project,

00:24:21.730 --> 00:24:23.470
where you basically say--

00:24:23.470 --> 00:24:26.110
you look at all these MGM
movie musicals and The Golden

00:24:26.110 --> 00:24:30.310
Age of Hollywood, and they're
building blocks of what we know

00:24:30.310 --> 00:24:31.384
and treasure today.

00:24:31.384 --> 00:24:32.800
I mean, "Hamilton"
is built on all

00:24:32.800 --> 00:24:34.600
this stuff in a lot of ways.

00:24:34.600 --> 00:24:37.560
But it was basically like,
well, OK, if on the town,

00:24:37.560 --> 00:24:41.280
the three sailors came back
to New York for a day off,

00:24:41.280 --> 00:24:43.480
but they really were
sailors, they really

00:24:43.480 --> 00:24:45.460
were coming off the
battlefield, they really

00:24:45.460 --> 00:24:49.810
had been through three years
of arms being ripped off

00:24:49.810 --> 00:24:52.660
and heads being blown
off and ships going out

00:24:52.660 --> 00:24:54.880
from underneath
their feet, what's

00:24:54.880 --> 00:24:57.520
the truth about what this
country really went through?

00:24:57.520 --> 00:25:01.570
And then that led to this idea
of, what kind of a country

00:25:01.570 --> 00:25:04.360
just glossed over so
much of this stuff

00:25:04.360 --> 00:25:07.720
and turned it into the greatest
generation when we know,

00:25:07.720 --> 00:25:10.510
those of us that have these
parents that lived through it,

00:25:10.510 --> 00:25:14.200
they became alcoholics because
they're numb to their pain?

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:16.000
And it was just this
amazing dichotomy

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:17.890
between what we
think of and what

00:25:17.890 --> 00:25:22.270
we hold onto as our mythology
from mid-20th century

00:25:22.270 --> 00:25:25.850
and how we just look at
it as this shining, almost

00:25:25.850 --> 00:25:27.010
Emerald City.

00:25:27.010 --> 00:25:27.869
But those of us--

00:25:27.869 --> 00:25:29.410
you close the door
behind it, and you

00:25:29.410 --> 00:25:31.420
remember grandpa was a mess.

00:25:31.420 --> 00:25:34.260
And why was grandpa a mess?

00:25:34.260 --> 00:25:37.550
And so that's really
where the idea was born.

00:25:37.550 --> 00:25:41.350
So the cliches and the tropes
in this story were intended.

00:25:41.350 --> 00:25:42.940
They just were
intended to be looked

00:25:42.940 --> 00:25:47.099
at from a very, very raw
and realistic point of view.

00:25:47.099 --> 00:25:49.390
ALAN SEALES: And then, so
how did it make it from paper

00:25:49.390 --> 00:25:50.880
into the Paper Mill
Playhouse-- right?--

00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:52.046
is where you workshopped it?

00:25:52.046 --> 00:25:55.750
ROBERT TAYLOR: Yes, we
had a number of readings

00:25:55.750 --> 00:25:58.390
only six months after we
finished the first draft.

00:25:58.390 --> 00:26:01.420
We finished the first draft
in about three months' time.

00:26:01.420 --> 00:26:04.150
Six months later, we had our
first reading here in New York.

00:26:04.150 --> 00:26:05.740
And many of these
people were involved

00:26:05.740 --> 00:26:09.200
in the very first
reading, and then

00:26:09.200 --> 00:26:13.660
a couple of subsequent readings,
and then a big lab workshop

00:26:13.660 --> 00:26:17.500
at Lincoln Center, and
then Paper Mill Playhouse

00:26:17.500 --> 00:26:20.080
a year later.

00:26:20.080 --> 00:26:24.400
And from there, our producers
decided we were ready.

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:26.350
ALAN SEALES: Many of
them are here tonight.

00:26:26.350 --> 00:26:28.460
They swarmed in for this thing.

00:26:28.460 --> 00:26:29.100
I love it.

00:26:29.100 --> 00:26:30.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:30.250 --> 00:26:32.166
RICHARD OBERACKER: They
just wanted the food--

00:26:32.166 --> 00:26:33.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:33.220 --> 00:26:34.480
--which is awesome.

00:26:34.480 --> 00:26:35.267
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:35.267 --> 00:26:36.850
ALAN SEALES: [INAUDIBLE]
to truck pit.

00:26:36.850 --> 00:26:37.808
They liked the dessert.

00:26:37.808 --> 00:26:39.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:39.190 --> 00:26:42.970
So for the cast here, being
as young as all of you are,

00:26:42.970 --> 00:26:46.060
I assume none of you were
actually in World War II.

00:26:46.060 --> 00:26:47.599
How did you prepare
for these roles?

00:26:47.599 --> 00:26:48.640
Did you talk to veterans?

00:26:48.640 --> 00:26:51.874
Did you get a feel for
what they went through?

00:26:51.874 --> 00:26:52.540
COREY COTT: Yes.

00:26:52.540 --> 00:26:58.510
So some of us are wearing these
six pins that you guys see.

00:26:58.510 --> 00:27:00.790
It represents an organization
called Got Your 6,

00:27:00.790 --> 00:27:04.150
which is this incredible
vets organization that really

00:27:04.150 --> 00:27:07.450
attempts to re-fabricate
the stereotype of veterans

00:27:07.450 --> 00:27:09.220
in our society and
how they're actually

00:27:09.220 --> 00:27:11.030
doing incredible
things for our society.

00:27:11.030 --> 00:27:14.800
They're not to be pitied
or looked down upon.

00:27:14.800 --> 00:27:17.290
But they're actually making
our society and culture

00:27:17.290 --> 00:27:18.080
more stable.

00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:19.840
And so one of the
things they do is

00:27:19.840 --> 00:27:24.907
they look at different pieces of
entertainment films, TV shows.

00:27:24.907 --> 00:27:26.740
And we're actually the
very first stage show

00:27:26.740 --> 00:27:29.950
to be accredited by Got Your 6
as an accurate representation

00:27:29.950 --> 00:27:32.110
of a veteran's story.

00:27:32.110 --> 00:27:33.490
So they came and saw our show.

00:27:33.490 --> 00:27:35.948
And they actually consulted on
the script with our writers,

00:27:35.948 --> 00:27:38.710
and gave us feedback,
and have been with us

00:27:38.710 --> 00:27:41.747
and guiding us for almost our
entire Broadway-- certainly

00:27:41.747 --> 00:27:43.830
our Broadway experience
even before Broadway, too.

00:27:43.830 --> 00:27:45.760
And so we had a
two-hour sit-down

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:47.980
where we, as the cast,
the Donny Nova Band,

00:27:47.980 --> 00:27:51.490
got to talk with them and just
ask them anything we wanted to,

00:27:51.490 --> 00:27:53.770
and they just gave us--
there was about 10 vets or so

00:27:53.770 --> 00:27:56.897
from all different branches,
and gave us their thoughts

00:27:56.897 --> 00:27:59.230
and insight, and were very
honest and vulnerable with us

00:27:59.230 --> 00:28:01.690
about their experiences in
combat and losing friends,

00:28:01.690 --> 00:28:03.440
and how they deal with that.

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:06.880
And that by far-- that
took our entire experience

00:28:06.880 --> 00:28:09.910
in show and script to
a whole other level.

00:28:09.910 --> 00:28:11.800
But paired with
that, we've also done

00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:14.170
our own individual research
by reading many memoirs

00:28:14.170 --> 00:28:17.830
and watching endless
documentaries in everything

00:28:17.830 --> 00:28:22.287
from "Band of Brothers" to
"Patton," everything out there.

00:28:22.287 --> 00:28:24.370
I mean, there's so many
resources on World War II,

00:28:24.370 --> 00:28:24.900
especially.

00:28:24.900 --> 00:28:28.150
But veterans today have
been a huge resource for us.

00:28:28.150 --> 00:28:29.650
LAURA OSNES: And
just last night, we

00:28:29.650 --> 00:28:35.020
had a group of Gold Star women,
wives and sisters and mothers

00:28:35.020 --> 00:28:36.900
who have lost men in battle.

00:28:36.900 --> 00:28:38.400
It was just women
last night, right?

00:28:38.400 --> 00:28:40.420
There weren't the guys then.

00:28:40.420 --> 00:28:43.030
Formed this organization
called taps.org,

00:28:43.030 --> 00:28:45.640
which stands for
Tragedy Assistance--

00:28:45.640 --> 00:28:47.167
COREY COTT: Survive--

00:28:47.167 --> 00:28:48.250
LAURA OSNES: What's the P?

00:28:48.250 --> 00:28:51.032
Tragedy Assistant--
yeah, it says on there.

00:28:51.032 --> 00:28:51.865
Tragedy Assistance--

00:28:51.865 --> 00:28:54.010
COREY COTT: I've
got it right here.

00:28:54.010 --> 00:28:56.290
Tragedy Assistance
Program for Survivors.

00:28:56.290 --> 00:29:00.160
LAURA OSNES: Program for
Survivors, so family members

00:29:00.160 --> 00:29:04.510
who have survived and had
family members that died

00:29:04.510 --> 00:29:06.820
in having to do with the war.

00:29:06.820 --> 00:29:09.940
And we had just an amazing
little reception with them

00:29:09.940 --> 00:29:10.480
last night.

00:29:10.480 --> 00:29:12.480
And it was incredible
to hear their stories.

00:29:12.480 --> 00:29:15.210
And they were in
awe of the show.

00:29:15.210 --> 00:29:17.820
And we were just talking
about how they made a point

00:29:17.820 --> 00:29:19.999
to say how truthful it was.

00:29:19.999 --> 00:29:22.290
They could relate so much to
so many of the characters,

00:29:22.290 --> 00:29:25.680
and to my character, especially,
because she's a widow,

00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:30.930
and just how they felt safe, and
that they could laugh with us

00:29:30.930 --> 00:29:31.860
and cry with us.

00:29:31.860 --> 00:29:33.960
And that was really
an incredible honor.

00:29:33.960 --> 00:29:36.240
And I'm fueled to do
the show again tonight,

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:40.560
because we had, again,
one-on-one firsthand

00:29:40.560 --> 00:29:42.720
interactions with people
who have gone through what

00:29:42.720 --> 00:29:43.980
our characters
have gone through,

00:29:43.980 --> 00:29:45.885
and that's the really
special thing about it.

00:29:45.885 --> 00:29:47.551
GEOFF PACKARD: And
the interesting thing

00:29:47.551 --> 00:29:50.010
about the research,
for me, was that you

00:29:50.010 --> 00:29:53.280
get cast in a show where you
get to play a combat veteran who

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:55.050
just comes back from the war.

00:29:55.050 --> 00:29:58.050
In particular, my
character has struggles

00:29:58.050 --> 00:30:00.090
with obsessive
compulsive disorder

00:30:00.090 --> 00:30:02.370
and is a germaphobe,
and really interesting

00:30:02.370 --> 00:30:04.840
things you get to
take on as an actor.

00:30:04.840 --> 00:30:06.330
So you focus on that.

00:30:06.330 --> 00:30:09.030
And for the first part of my
experience with "Bandstand,"

00:30:09.030 --> 00:30:12.030
I focused on what
those differences were.

00:30:12.030 --> 00:30:16.267
Then we met with these
veterans, and they all

00:30:16.267 --> 00:30:17.100
told us their story.

00:30:17.100 --> 00:30:19.710
And it was an overwhelming
idea that they

00:30:19.710 --> 00:30:25.020
wanted to be portrayed as human
and not victims or heroes,

00:30:25.020 --> 00:30:26.910
that they really
wanted us to focus

00:30:26.910 --> 00:30:29.640
on what the human
aspect of these people

00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:36.090
were-- they were fathers and
sons and lovers and humorists.

00:30:36.090 --> 00:30:37.561
And we found it--

00:30:37.561 --> 00:30:39.310
with this interesting
thing with our show,

00:30:39.310 --> 00:30:40.268
it takes place in 1945.

00:30:40.268 --> 00:30:43.350
And we have this great
device of swing music

00:30:43.350 --> 00:30:45.780
to really represent that.

00:30:45.780 --> 00:30:48.600
So a lot of research,
also, with learning

00:30:48.600 --> 00:30:50.230
how to play the instruments.

00:30:50.230 --> 00:30:52.590
We also had to learn
what swing music

00:30:52.590 --> 00:30:54.630
meant to that time period.

00:30:54.630 --> 00:31:00.060
And it, in a lot of
ways, helped these people

00:31:00.060 --> 00:31:03.540
get through these
horrible things,

00:31:03.540 --> 00:31:06.300
but also let them release
all the fun stuff.

