00:44:06.950 --> 00:44:09.922
was so anti-military.

00:44:09.922 --> 00:44:11.630
And he said something
along the lines of,

00:44:11.630 --> 00:44:14.450
this is the first time
I've felt truly free of--

00:44:14.450 --> 00:44:16.700
truly proud of being a
veteran, that was what he said.

00:44:16.700 --> 00:44:19.280
This is the first time I've felt
truly proud of being a veteran.

00:44:19.280 --> 00:44:20.210
There's a bunch
of those stories.

00:44:20.210 --> 00:44:21.200
Fleet Week was amazing.

00:44:21.200 --> 00:44:22.574
When Fleet Week
was happening, we

00:44:22.574 --> 00:44:24.572
had tons of vets
in all the time.

00:44:24.572 --> 00:44:25.280
COREY COTT: Yeah.

00:44:25.280 --> 00:44:27.710
And even people that
didn't specifically serve,

00:44:27.710 --> 00:44:29.450
there's so many
stories of them either

00:44:29.450 --> 00:44:32.570
being related to their
grandfathers, or their uncles,

00:44:32.570 --> 00:44:34.730
or dads, or
brothers, or sisters,

00:44:34.730 --> 00:44:37.670
or moms who have
served in some way.

00:44:37.670 --> 00:44:41.090
And in a lot of
ways, I think there's

00:44:41.090 --> 00:44:44.720
been an expectation
to come see our show

00:44:44.720 --> 00:44:46.070
with this idea of swing music.

00:44:46.070 --> 00:44:48.590
And "Bandstand," you
have a certain idea

00:44:48.590 --> 00:44:49.906
of what this could be.

00:44:49.906 --> 00:44:51.530
And then you come--
and a lot of people

00:44:51.530 --> 00:44:53.510
have said they've
come and been taken

00:44:53.510 --> 00:44:56.330
to an experience, an
emotional journey,

00:44:56.330 --> 00:45:01.067
that they didn't expect, and
felt that not only did they

00:45:01.067 --> 00:45:03.650
have a good time and felt like
they experienced a great story,

00:45:03.650 --> 00:45:05.150
but that they felt
like they honored

00:45:05.150 --> 00:45:09.410
their relatives, that they were
taken to a place that respected

00:45:09.410 --> 00:45:10.800
them.

00:45:10.800 --> 00:45:12.300
GEOFF PACKARD: We
also got to meet--

00:45:12.300 --> 00:45:13.580
he wasn't a veteran,
but he was one

00:45:13.580 --> 00:45:15.913
of the most interesting people
I've ever met in my life.

00:45:15.913 --> 00:45:18.290
There's a 19-year-old guy
named-- what's his name, Rob?

00:45:18.290 --> 00:45:19.153
LAURA OSNES: Rishi.

00:45:19.153 --> 00:45:20.060
ROBERT TAYLOR: Rishi Sharma.

00:45:20.060 --> 00:45:21.226
GEOFF PACKARD: Rishi Sharma.

00:45:21.226 --> 00:45:25.130
And he was from California,
graduated high school,

00:45:25.130 --> 00:45:27.650
and was obsessed
with this mission

00:45:27.650 --> 00:45:32.930
to meet and record all of
the living American World War

00:45:32.930 --> 00:45:35.007
II veterans that
are still present.

00:45:35.007 --> 00:45:35.840
And he did the math.

00:45:35.840 --> 00:45:38.330
There's something like
however many die every day.

00:45:38.330 --> 00:45:41.762
So he mapped out that there's
four years until they all die.

00:45:41.762 --> 00:45:42.470
ALAN SEALES: Wow.

00:45:42.470 --> 00:45:45.095
GEOFF PACKARD: And so he's been,
for the past year and a half--

00:45:45.095 --> 00:45:46.636
RICHARD OBERACKER:
He's been doing it

00:45:46.636 --> 00:45:47.762
about two and a half years.

00:45:47.762 --> 00:45:49.636
GEOFF PACKARD: He goes
throughout the country

00:45:49.636 --> 00:45:50.700
and contacts these men--

00:45:50.700 --> 00:45:53.630
combat veterans, in particular--
and sits down with them,

00:45:53.630 --> 00:45:56.180
and talks and interviews
them for about--

00:45:56.180 --> 00:45:58.970
ROBERT TAYLOR: And gets their
actual stories, their combat

00:45:58.970 --> 00:46:00.870
stories, on camera.

00:46:00.870 --> 00:46:01.730
It's really--

00:46:01.730 --> 00:46:03.080
RICHARD OBERACKER: It's
like the Shoah Foundation

00:46:03.080 --> 00:46:05.559
for the Holocaust that Spielberg
was heavily involved with.

00:46:05.559 --> 00:46:07.100
And so he's archiving
all this stuff.

00:46:07.100 --> 00:46:09.475
And he's really the only one
in the world who's doing it.

00:46:09.475 --> 00:46:10.400
He's 19 years old.

00:46:10.400 --> 00:46:12.320
GEOFF PACKARD: And
immediately after the show,

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:13.220
we're like, well,
are you going to make

00:46:13.220 --> 00:46:14.282
a documentary about this?

00:46:14.282 --> 00:46:16.490
And he's like, no, no, no,
I give it to the veterans.

00:46:16.490 --> 00:46:18.950
It's not really about what
goes into the footage,

00:46:18.950 --> 00:46:21.470
it's about these guys
getting it off their chest.

00:46:21.470 --> 00:46:23.610
And so immediately,
Corey and I were like,

00:46:23.610 --> 00:46:27.190
yeah, man, I was feeling good
about the story we were telling

00:46:27.190 --> 00:46:28.970
until we meet this 19-year-old.

00:46:28.970 --> 00:46:31.460
But that's the best
part about this show

00:46:31.460 --> 00:46:33.080
is that there are a lot of--

00:46:33.080 --> 00:46:34.910
hopefully, when they
come and see it,

00:46:34.910 --> 00:46:38.810
somebody asks a family
member, wasn't uncle so-and-so

00:46:38.810 --> 00:46:39.380
in the war?

00:46:39.380 --> 00:46:40.280
What was his story?

00:46:40.280 --> 00:46:42.410
And that happened to each of us.

00:46:42.410 --> 00:46:44.450
On some level, we
go, yeah, tell me

00:46:44.450 --> 00:46:46.822
about Uncle Morty's
time in the--

00:46:46.822 --> 00:46:48.780
and all of a sudden, you
get these new stories,

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:53.380
or these old stories
come out anew.

00:46:53.380 --> 00:46:55.520
Our director, Andy,
came backstage

00:46:55.520 --> 00:46:58.370
after the Tony's and said--

00:46:58.370 --> 00:47:00.714
was it his uncle
or his grandfather?

00:47:00.714 --> 00:47:02.630
COREY COTT: Grandfather
was in the 4th Marines

00:47:02.630 --> 00:47:04.869
and had fought in the
Pacific, at Iwo Jima, and all

00:47:04.869 --> 00:47:05.660
these other places.

00:47:05.660 --> 00:47:06.350
GEOFF PACKARD: That's
the most common thing

00:47:06.350 --> 00:47:08.900
is that, I didn't know,
but so-and-so did this,

00:47:08.900 --> 00:47:11.760
or I didn't know, but my
next-door neighbor was a Gold

00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:12.710
Star member, whatever.

00:47:12.710 --> 00:47:13.751
LAURA OSNES: Yeah, right.

00:47:13.751 --> 00:47:17.090
ROBERT TAYLOR: And my dad
is a World War II vet.

00:47:17.090 --> 00:47:20.900
And all of the dads of the
kids I grew up with were.

00:47:20.900 --> 00:47:24.080
And there were so
many things about them

00:47:24.080 --> 00:47:29.060
that I couldn't explain why they
were these incredible people

00:47:29.060 --> 00:47:32.710
that had explosive tempers
and that were, very often,

00:47:32.710 --> 00:47:37.210
in fights and self-medicating.

00:47:37.210 --> 00:47:42.000
And it's been really--

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:45.340
it's opened up, for me,
just a window into what they

00:47:45.340 --> 00:47:48.540
were going through, writing the
show and working on the show.

00:47:48.540 --> 00:47:50.410
And that's what I've seen--

00:47:50.410 --> 00:47:53.300
other people who haven't
served themselves.

00:47:53.300 --> 00:47:56.650
But it's opened up such a window
of understanding into relatives

00:47:56.650 --> 00:48:01.200
and family members that--

00:48:01.200 --> 00:48:05.910
it's just amazing that they're
suddenly realizing, oh,

00:48:05.910 --> 00:48:09.360
that's probably why this man
has been so distant all my life,

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:15.480
or that's probably
why just the slightest

00:48:15.480 --> 00:48:19.312
thing can trigger a response
I would not have expected.

00:48:19.312 --> 00:48:21.270
ALAN SEALES: Well, we're
running short of time.

00:48:21.270 --> 00:48:23.859
We do have one more
performance from you guys

00:48:23.859 --> 00:48:24.900
I hope that you can give.

00:48:24.900 --> 00:48:28.000
But I want to take one question
over here before we're done.

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:30.500
AUDIENCE: So I know you guys
talked a lot about the research

00:48:30.500 --> 00:48:32.375
that you're doing to
develop your characters,

00:48:32.375 --> 00:48:34.000
so I guess my
question is in regards

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.750
to an understudy or a
swing, how much flexibility

00:48:36.750 --> 00:48:39.250
